urie</i> ‘merry, pleasant’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Merry   1. This surname is established in Ireland (perhaps as an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name; compare   Marmion  ) as well as England.","there has probably been some confusion with <b>Marriman</b>, probably an occupational name meaning ‘servant of <i>Mary</i>’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’, or perhaps a pet form of <i>Mary</i> using the hypocoristic suffix -<i>man</i>. The surname <i>Marriman</i> is now vanishingly rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Marmon","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Gloucestershire):","variant of   Marmion  .","variant of <b>Marriman</b>, an occupational name meaning ‘servant of Mary’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":3,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":28,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":41,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":50,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Marmion was born about 1287, in Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Marmion, was 28 and his mother, Margery de Nottingham, was 25. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Agnes. He died about 1350, in his hometown, at the age of 65, and was buried in Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England."},"et":{"Abt 1287–Abt 1350":"umbes 1287–umbes 1350","1287–1350":"1287–1350","1298–1360":"1298–1360","1320–1367":"1320–1367","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1331–1367":"1331–1367","1260–1331":"1260–1331","1263–1300":"1263–1300","1263":"1263","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","Abt 1350":"umbes 1350","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","Abt 1300":"umbes 1300","1367":"1367","ABT 1320":"umbes 1320","1300":"1300","Abt 1287":"umbes 1287","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1331":"1331","1298":"1298","1287":"1287","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England":"Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Checkenden,Oxfordshire,England":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Checkenden, Oxfordshire, England":"Checkendon, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1287–Abt 1350":"noin 1287–noin 1350","1287–1350":"1287–1350","1298–1